The paper discusses the use of Agent-Based Simulation (ABS) to understand management practices and their impact on retail performance. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Multi-Agent Systems (cs.MA) sub-category, which deals with the study of systems composed of multiple interacting agents. Additionally, the paper mentions the use of simulation to analyze dynamic and stochastic systems, which could place it in the Computational Engineering, Finance, and Science (cs.CE) sub-category. The paper also discusses the use of simulation to optimize management practices, which could place it in the Machine Learning (cs.LG) sub-category, as well as the Human-Computer Interaction (cs.HC) sub-category, which deals with the design and evaluation of interactive systems. Finally, the paper mentions the emergence of structures at the macro level as a result of the actions of agents, which could place it in the Social and Information Networks (cs.SI) sub-category, which deals with the study of social and information networks and their properties.
